<question-stem>
<para> How does the professor present the information about N-E-Os in this
lecture?<mediaExhibit frameType="mp3" mediaRef="toeflPrac10225.mp3"/></para>
</question-stem>
<answer-choice-set>
<answer-choice correct="yes"> By discussing the real and potential effects
of smaller to larger objects.</answer-choice>
<answer-choice> By detailing the debate over their actual existence</answer-choice>
<answer-choice> By explaining the effects of those objects throughout history
in chronological order</answer-choice>
<answer-choice> By comparing theories about why they hit the moon and Earth</answer-choice>
</answer-choice-set>
<explanation interaction="true">
<para> The professor begins by talking about a small asteroid that hit Tungusaka
and continues by discussing medium and then large sized N-E-O's. The structure
of this lecture is thus best represented by (A). Although the professor does
mention a debate (B), it is important in the last part of the talk. Some of
the effects are potential or theoretical and order is not chronological (C).
No theories for why N-E-Os hit the moon and Earth are discussed (D).</para>
</explanation>
